{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539614"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:44:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:44:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16682"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16682"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.07,0.65,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9373"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66320"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9373"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16682"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51769"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4078"},{"type":"tags","id":"4192"},{"type":"tags","id":"4193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4194"},{"type":"tags","id":"4195"},{"type":"tags","id":"4197"},{"type":"tags","id":"4540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4546"},{"type":"tags","id":"10948"},{"type":"tags","id":"10950"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22183"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66320"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with her partner with concerns about difficulty conceiving for the past 18 months. She reports irregular menstrual cycles with occasional intermenstrual bleeding. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her cervical screening test is normal and up to date. Her partner has had normal semen analysis results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Investigations reveal: follicle stimulating hormone 6.2 IU/L (3.5-12.5), luteinizing hormone 4.8 IU/L (2.4-12.6), day 21 progesterone 35 nmol/L (\u0026gt;30), and normal thyroid function tests. Transvaginal ultrasound shows a 15 mm echogenic lesion within the endometrial cavity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diagnostic laparoscopy and tube dye studies","Clomiphene citrate therapy","Hysteroscopy with polypectomy","Expectant management with serial ultrasound monitoring","Oral progestogen therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with subfertility and irregular menstrual bleeding. The transvaginal ultrasound finding of an endometrial polyp may be contributing to her fertility issues by interfering with embryo implantation and causing abnormal bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHysteroscopy with polypectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard treatment for endometrial polyps in women with subfertility. This procedure allows direct visualisation of the endometrial cavity, precise removal of the polyp, and histological examination of the tissue. Studies have shown improved pregnancy rates following polyp removal in women with unexplained infertility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnostic laparoscopy and tube dye studies\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were concerns about tubal patency or other pelvic pathology. However, the presence of an endometrial polyp should be addressed first as it represents a potentially correctable cause of subfertility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClomiphene citrate\u003C/strong\u003E therapy would be inappropriate without first addressing the structural abnormality within the uterine cavity. The patient\u0027s day 21 progesterone indicates ovulation is occurring, so ovulation induction is not indicated at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExpectant management\u003C/strong\u003E with serial ultrasound monitoring is not appropriate as the polyp is likely contributing to both the irregular bleeding and subfertility. Small polyps may spontaneously resolve, but in the context of infertility, active management is warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral progestogen\u003C/strong\u003E therapy may temporarily suppress polyp growth but will not remove the existing polyp. This approach would delay definitive treatment and potentially further delay conception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter polypectomy, if pregnancy is not achieved within a reasonable timeframe, further fertility investigations and treatments can be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endometrial polyps can contribute to infertility by interfering with implantation.","Hysteroscopic polypectomy is the gold standard treatment for endometrial polyps in women with infertility.","Transvaginal ultrasound is the initial imaging modality of choice for investigating abnormal uterine bleeding and subfertility."],"references":["Bougie O, Randle E, Thurston J, Magee B, Warshafsky C, Rittenberg D, et al. Guideline No. 447: Diagnosis and Management of Endometrial Polyps. J Obstet Gynaecol Can. 2024;46(3):102402.","Pereira N, Petrini AC, Lekovich JP, Elias RT, Spandorfer SD. Surgical Management of Endometrial Polyps in Infertile Women: A Comprehensive Review. Surg Res Pract. 2015;2015:914390. doi: 10.1155/2015/914390. Epub 2015 Aug 2. PMID: 26301260; PMCID: PMC4537769."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51769"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16682"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51769"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T18:49:10+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-29T18:49:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9373"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66320"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1540","links":{"self":"https://app.